			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Dealing with large sites myself in real life, my assumption is that this is not just a SW patch, but likely is a hardware installation for LDoN. As far as I can guess, each zone on each "server" runs on a single box. LDoN, to be scalable, will require a significantly different architecture. 
<br />

<br />
With that roll-out scheduled for two weeks from now, this is a logical time to be installing new servers, adjusting NAT and load balancers, and all those nasty things. From experience, significant changes to network topology is a non-trivial thing and requires a huge amount of checking before bringing everything back on line.
<br />

<br />
I agree that software patches themselves <span style="font-style: italic">could </span>be done in under an hour, including verification, but why? SoE does not have an uptime commitment. If I were in their network ops, I would take my time and do it during light-usage hours, just as they do now.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
