				<td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=80608&amp;sid=8fb6c3fd0000ed01714b7b255e0a77be#80608"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Wed Aug 27, 2003 4:24 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: Diary of an Update...</span></td>
				<td valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=80608&amp;sid=8fb6c3fd0000ed01714b7b255e0a77be"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>   </td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The Tuesday/3am update was particularly involved.  It involved updates of all kinds.  Wherever we can, the different groups in the company try to "ride" each others downtime, such that we end up with fewer outages overall.
<br />

<br />
Many of these things happened simultaneously, wherever it was possible, to ensure that we had the minimum amount of downtime we could get away with.
<br />

<br />
1) Our network folks needed to upgrade software that the firewalls run.  This caused our backend systems to all need to be restarted.
<br />

<br />
2) Our database folks needed to do some maintenance and upgrades to their applications and tables that required a downtime and a restart.
<br />

<br />
3) EQ the game needed to go through its own standard data update cycle (~2 hours)
<br />

<br />
4) EQ's characters (~14 million) needed to all be converted over to the format that will be used from here forward which, as you correctly guessed, was largely caused by the entirely new item system that supports augmentations. (~6 hours by itself)
<br />

<br />
5) EQ's billing and subscription services had to be upgraded.  Whenever we do this, we extend the downtime an extra half hour to make sure that the live login and billing services can be tested in an internal-only-locked mode before letting anyone in. (~1 hour)
<br />

<br />
6) And just for good measure, given the sheer number of updates that all happened at once, QA, CS, and the EQLive team all checked a character of their own, on every server, to ensure that the character conversion and the rest of the update all went well, and items worked the same way that they did the day before, despite being completely rewritten. (~45 minutes)
<br />

<br />
7) Once that was all done and our confidence was high, as a last minute check, we opened Ayonae a few minutes early and about ten people sat on that server watching for a flood of petitions in case we missed anything obvious. (~30 minutes)
<br />

<br />
8) When that flood of petitions never came and 1000 or so people made it onto the server, the rest of the worlds were opened.
<br />

<br />
Hope that explains a few things.  It's a lot more involved than.  "Copy files, start servers."  The updates where that's the only thing going on usually last about 2-3 hours, as a number of them have in the past two years, including the brief update last night.  :)  
<br />

<br />
Best,
<br />

<br />
- Scott Hartsman
<br />
Technical Director, EverQuest</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
