<br />

<br />
Let me know if you're getting low on fingers. :)
<br />

<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Darlatan wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
Does this mean that anytime all servers are brought down, there's a minimum of 2 hours to get them back up again?
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I wouldn't say that's the absolute minimum, but that's a good estimate given an "low-to-average" load of what needs to be updated most frequently, with updates to both the client and servers.
<br />

<br />
Ops has downed servers when we need to update, say, just items, and had them back in a half hour.  That's about the theoretical minimum for that many servers.  
<br />

<br />
The large number of machines really complicates things. Our Ops group has to remote-restart well over 1000 boxes when any kind of update happens. 
<br />

<br />
A lot of the time, it's the sheer process of remote controlling that many computers, across multiple installations in two or three contries, and then ensuring they all actually did what they were asked to do, that takes a bit of time.
<br />

<br />

<br />
- Scott Hartsman
<br />
Technical Director, EverQuest</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
